"response_text": "The average degree of deviation from recommended livestock stocking levels begins near zero at time step 0, indicating baseline adherence to optimal stocking. Over time, deviations exhibit spatially heterogeneous patterns, with persistent negative values (understocking) emerging in northern zones around time step 25, potentially reflecting risk-averse adjustments to early-stage climatic variability. By time step 50, deviations in western households trend positively, driven by the cumulative effects of rainfall-driven pasture recovery and social learning diffusion, peaking at ~0.35 in central households at 75 steps before plateauing. The northern gradients flatten entirely by 90 steps, suggesting adaptation to spatial vegetation heterogeneity. Risk sensitivity (risk-att-init=0.5) aligns these deviations with climatic shocks: negative deviations correlate with precipitation deficits in early steps, while post-70 increases in positive deviations mirror delayed recovery dynamics. Household 15 and 21 consistently exhibit the highest deviations, indicating localized peaks in adaptive lag. The final plateau suggests equilibrium between risk-adjusted stocking and resource constraints under homogenous strategy adoption. "  
}

